[4]
Date: 6 Sep 2016
Source: OIE [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?reportid=20919


Report type Follow-up report No. 4
-------------------
New outbreaks (1)
Outbreak 1 (8): Langatte, Moselle
Date of start of the outbreak: 29 Aug 2016
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 322 / 1 / 1 / 0 / 0
Affected population: A bovine brutally died on 29 Aug 2016. It belonged to a 6-bovine batch that was treated with antibiotics.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Contact with infected animal(s) at grazing/watering; Fomites (humans, vehicles, feed, etc.)
Epidemiological comments: Reoccurrence. A history of anthrax cases on these pastures is known. Vaccination became mandatory in 10 municipalities of the infected area in the department of Moselle.

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Maisons Alfort Animal health laboratory, ANSES (National laboratory) / Cattle / bacteriological examination / 1 Sep 2016 / Positive

Future Reporting: The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[After years of relative calm, this epidemic in northeast France is a re-educating experience. Once these districts return to their normal state, it will be necessary to implement a compulsory annual vaccination policy each spring for at least the next 5-6 years. The losses in the early affected herds have been significant, reflecting a slow reaction in each case. As the farmers became more aware, the losses were minimal. A lesson to be shared. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4469824,100.]
